Doosan, Evergrande, LG, NAB, SM Investments: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-03-02T20:57:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-02/doosan-lg-nab-sm-investments-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding Japan.
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Doosan Infracore Co. (042670 KS): The company plans to
spend 60.1 billion won ($53 million) building a new construction
machine plant in  Brazil  by the end of 2018, according to a
regulatory filing to the Korea Exchange. The stock fell 3.3
percent to 24,800 won.    Evergrande Real Estate Group Ltd . (3333 HK): Net income for
the year ended Dec. 31 may have a “significant increase” from
a year earlier, the company said in a statement to the Hong Kong
stock exchange, without giving details. The stock fell 0.5
percent to HK$3.76.    Far Eastern International Bank  (2845 TT): The bank has held
talks with Japanese, South Korean and North American investors
seeking to buy a stake in the Taipei-based bank, President Eli
Hong said. The bank may allow an acquirer to take a stake of up
to 15 percent in the company, with a deal likely to include a
board seat, he said. The stock fell 1.9 percent to NT$13.30.    LG Electronics Inc . (066570 KS): The world’s third-largest
maker of mobile phones is working to develop its own chips for
smartphones to strengthen the company’s handset business, said
Ken Hong, a spokesman for Seoul-based LG. The stock gained 0.5
percent to 111,500 won.    National Australia Bank Ltd . (NAB AU): The bank sold A$700
million ($712 million) of bonds due in March 2018, according to
an e-mailed statement from the lender. The notes were priced to
yield 187.25 basis points more than similar-maturity government
debt, or 145 basis points more than the asset swap rate,
according to the statement. The stock fell 0.1 percent to
A$25.55.  Poly Glass Fibre (M) Bhd. (PGF MK): The Malaysian maker of
fiber glass wool said it will spend more than 10 million ringgit
to expand its plant capacity by 50 percent, according to a
company statement. The shares were unchanged at 36.5 sen.    RFM Corp . (RFM PM): The Philippine food and drinks company
said it will pay 2.97 centavos a share in cash dividends, a
stock-exchange filing showed. The stock decreased 3 percent to
1.60 pesos.    SM Investments Corp . (SM PM): The owner of the largest
Philippine bank and biggest shopping mall operator said profit
rose 15 percent to 18.4 billion pesos ($307 million). The stock
fell 0.9 percent to 457 pesos.    Springsoft Inc . (2473 TT): The Taiwanese  software developer 
plans to buy back 4 million common shares, or 1.92 percent of
its outstanding stock, at between NT$25 and NT$53 each from
March 3 to May 2, the company said in a stock-exchange filing.
The stock rose 0.4 percent to NT$35.50.  To contact the reporter on this story:
